<paragraph id="F236F758EC39FFC9FF7E69F6FC62CE54" blockId="21.[154,1111,856,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FF7E69F6FE8CC9B0" box="[194,296,922,946]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">Anatomy</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="6AB2EBDDEC39FFC9FE8669F5FE0CC9B3" box="[314,424,921,945]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="20.[159,175,1415,1437]" captionTargetBox="[330,948,581,1377]" captionTargetId="figure-104@20.[326,949,578,1383]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIG. 20. Limatula smithi. Sta. 189, semi-diagrammatic view of the anatomy from the right side. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5250763" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5250763/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">figures 20</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="6AB2EBDDEC39FFC9FE0B69F5FE76C9B3" box="[439,466,921,945]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[154,170,748,770]" captionTargetBox="[389,877,171,712]" captionTargetId="figure-340@21.[387,878,170,715]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 21. Limatula smithi. Sta. 191, inner view of left mantle margin to show disposition of the tentacles and papillae. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5250767" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5250767/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">21</figureCitation>
). The anatomy is similar to that described for 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FBB969F6FF72C9D0" baseAuthorityName="Jeffreys" baseAuthorityYear="1876" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="subovata">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FBB969F6FF72C9D0" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">L. subovata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FEA569D6FE60C9D0" box="[281,452,954,978]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FEA569D6FE1BC9D0" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="2010" box="[281,447,954,978]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="margaretae">L. margaretae</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Mantle margin less broad than other species described here, each sensory fold bears 14–15 tentacles, small papillate ones alternate with larger finger-like tentacles of which latter three ventral-most ones are largest, postero-dorsal anal tentacle on each side separate from other tentacles, gills extensive, both demibranchs with ascending and descending lamellae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F236F758EC39FFC9FF7E6E33FDC2CC03" blockId="21.[154,1111,856,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FF7E6E33FE89CE75" box="[194,301,1119,1143]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">Remarks.</emphasis>
The specimens from Valorous sta. 11, which are part of the Jeffreys collection in the USNM are labelled 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FDF06EECFCB4CE9A" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" box="[588,784,1152,1176]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FDF06EECFCB4CE9A" box="[588,784,1152,1176]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">Limatula confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but are the same species as described here. The label is old but probably not the original. Curiously, 
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FBBC6ECCFF45CEDB" author="JEFFREYS, J. G." pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="424 - 436" refId="ref19258" refString="JEFFREYS, J. G., 1876, New and peculiar Mollusca of the Pecten, Mytilus and Arca families, procured by the ' Valorous' expedition, Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 18, 424 - 436." type="journal article" year="1876">Jeffreys (1876)</bibRefCitation>
does not report on specimens from this station. What he did describe were specimens from the adjacent Valorous sta. 12. These he identified as 
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FBA06E8EFF03CF19" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FBA06E8EFBF3CEF8" authorityName="Bruguiere" authorityYear="1797" box="[1052,1111,1250,1274]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Lima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Lima</taxonomicName>
(
</emphasis>
~ 
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FF7E6F6FFE90CF19" box="[194,308,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FF7E6F6FFE88CF19" authorityName="S. V. Wood" authorityYear="1839" box="[194,300,1283,1307]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Limatula</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FE816F6FFDEFCF19" authority="S. V. Wood. This" authorityName="S. V. Wood. This" authorityYear="1839" box="[317,587,1283,1307]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ovata">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FE816F6FFEDDCF19" box="[317,377,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">ovata</emphasis>
S. V. Wood. This
</taxonomicName>
latter was an identification that 
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FC786F6FFBF2CF19" author="SMITH, A. E." box="[964,1110,1283,1307]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="1 - 341" refId="ref22552" refString="SMITH, A. E., 1885, Report on the Lamellibranchiata, Report of the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger During the Years 1873 - 76, Zoology, XIII, 1 - 341." type="journal article" year="1885">Smith (1885)</bibRefCitation>
disagreed with and Smith included the specimens from Valorous sta. 12 with 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FBA06F48FEDBCF5F" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Lima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="confusa" subGenus="Limatula">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FBA06F48FEDBCF5F" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">Lima (Limatula) confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which he described from various Challenger stations (see Appendix). Presumably the specific name refers in part to Jeffreys’ misidentification and partly to the fact that 
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FE6F6FEBFDDECF9D" author="JEFFREYS, J. G." box="[467,634,1415,1439]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="424 - 436" refId="ref19258" refString="JEFFREYS, J. G., 1876, New and peculiar Mollusca of the Pecten, Mytilus and Arca families, procured by the ' Valorous' expedition, Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 18, 424 - 436." type="journal article" year="1876">Jeffreys (1876)</bibRefCitation>
reported that there were about 50 radial ribs whereas 
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FE8C6FC4FE66CFC2" author="SMITH, A. E." box="[304,450,1448,1472]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="1 - 341" refId="ref22552" refString="SMITH, A. E., 1885, Report on the Lamellibranchiata, Report of the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger During the Years 1873 - 76, Zoology, XIII, 1 - 341." type="journal article" year="1885">Smith (1885)</bibRefCitation>
reported that there were 
<quantity id="35715ABDEC39FFC9FD5B6FC4FC84CFC2" box="[743,800,1448,1472]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" unit="in" value="30.0">30 in</quantity>
his specimens 
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FC766FC4FC56CFC2" box="[970,1010,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">and</emphasis>
those of 
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FF266FA4FEE5CFE2" author="JEFFREYS, J. G." box="[154,321,1480,1504]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="424 - 436" refId="ref19258" refString="JEFFREYS, J. G., 1876, New and peculiar Mollusca of the Pecten, Mytilus and Arca families, procured by the ' Valorous' expedition, Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 18, 424 - 436." type="journal article" year="1876">Jeffreys (1876)</bibRefCitation>
from Valorous sta. 12. It would appear then that Jeffreys probably referred specimens to the wrong station.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F236F758EC39FFCAFF7E6C64FE75CB0A" blockId="21.[154,1111,856,1733]" lastBlockId="22.[159,1116,173,430]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="2611" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">
Apart from the fact that 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FE5E6C64FDE3CC22" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="2010" box="[482,583,1544,1568]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="smithi">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FE5E6C64FDE3CC22" box="[482,583,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">L. smithi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a greater number of ribs than 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FC666C64FBEBCC22" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" box="[986,1103,1544,1568]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Lima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FC666C64FBEBCC22" box="[986,1103,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">L. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it also possesses an internal central groove, which 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FD486C45FCC8CC43" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" box="[756,876,1577,1601]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Lima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FD486C45FCC8CC43" box="[756,876,1577,1601]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">L. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is said not to have (
<bibRefCitation id="96188AA9EC39FFC9FF1D6C26FEE3CC60" author="JEFFREYS, J. G." box="[161,327,1610,1634]" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" pagination="424 - 436" refId="ref19258" refString="JEFFREYS, J. G., 1876, New and peculiar Mollusca of the Pecten, Mytilus and Arca families, procured by the ' Valorous' expedition, Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 18, 424 - 436." type="journal article" year="1876">Jeffreys, 1876</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FDBA6C26FDCACC60" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="2010" box="[518,622,1610,1634]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="smithi">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FDBA6C26FDCACC60" box="[518,622,1610,1634]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">L. smithi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a less oblique outline, is less broad and the posterior margin is shallowly curved giving the shell, particularly of moderate- and larger-sized specimens, a characteristic outline, in which the anterior and posterior margins appear almost parallel. 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC39FFC9FD6E6CC1FC66CCC7" baseAuthorityName="Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[722,962,1709,1733]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hyperborea">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC39FFC9FD6E6CC1FC66CCC7" box="[722,962,1709,1733]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="2610">Limatula hyperborea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a northern shallow-water species, has a similar outline, although the latter has fewer ribs that do not extend as far dorsally as those of 
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC3AFFCAFD396AA3FC0CCAE5" box="[645,936,207,231]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611">
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC3AFFCAFD396AA3FD4BCAE5" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="2010" box="[645,751,207,231]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="smithi">L. smithi</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC3AFFCAFD416AA3FC0CCAE5" authorityName="S. V. Wood. This" authorityYear="1839" box="[765,936,207,231]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Limatula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ovata">Limatula ovata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
like 
<taxonomicName id="35898CDBEC3AFFCAFC596AA3FBF8CAE5" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" box="[997,1116,207,231]" class="Bivalvia" family="Limidae" genus="Lima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Limida" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="C0FD2B4AEC3AFFCAFC596AA3FBF8CAE5" box="[997,1116,207,231]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611">L. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a much broader shell.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F236F758EC3AFFCAFF7B6B7CFCA6CBAC" blockId="22.[159,1116,173,430]" pageId="22" pageNumber="2611">In this species there is no evidence that the gills are used as brood pouches nor that the eggs are retained within the mantle cavity. This species has the smallest prodissoconch of all the species described here and it may well be that there is a lecithotrophic planktonic phase. The species is named after A. E. Smith who described the bivalves of the Challenger Expedition.</paragraph>
